This directory holds the two ends of the cage boundary plus the batteries-included wrapper around them: `ctx_cage.rs` builds and drives a cage session from the host side, `ctx_cage_client.rs` runs inside the cage and brokers tool calls back out over a Unix socket, and `ctx_run.rs` is the one-command billed entry point that wraps `ctx_cage`'s lifecycle with pre/post steps (env loading, summary refresh, hook check).

The two cage-facing binaries share exit-code truncation (`i32`/`u32` → `u8`, out-of-range collapses to 1) and the same `emit()`-style suppressed-write convention for stdout/stderr, satisfying repo-wide lint rules against direct print macros — a change to one convention should be checked against the other file. `ctx_cage.rs` and `ctx_run.rs` both resolve sibling binaries (`ctx-verify`, `ctx-context`, `ctx-scan`) relative to `current_exe()`'s directory using the same `CTX_*_BIN` env-var override names; keep that resolution logic consistent if either changes. `ctx_cage_client.rs` is the counterpart that actually uses the socket protocol (`ctx_cage::protocol`) these resolved binaries are bound into at `/cage/bin` — a protocol frame change requires updating both the client's `replay_response` and whatever host-side broker writes those frames.

Spend gating differs by design across the two host-side entry points: `ctx_cage.rs` requires explicit `--allow-spend`/env var for billed modes, while `ctx_run.rs` treats invocation itself as authorization — don't conflate the two when adding a new entry point. Neither `ctx_cage.rs` nor `ctx_run.rs` ever carries an API key for the cage/agent itself; `ctx_run.rs`'s optional env file only feeds the post-run `ctx-scan` child, never the session.

No intent.md exists to check divergence against.